{{short description|9th-century Muslim hadith scholar}} {{Infobox Muslim scholar |era = [[Islamic golden age]]| |image = |caption = |name = Sulaiman ibn Ahmad At-Tabarani |title= Al-Tabarani |birth_date = 260 AH [874 CE] |death_date = 360 AH [971 CE] |Maddhab = |school_tradition = Sunni |ethnicity = |region = |notable_ideas= |main_interests = [[Hadith]] |influences = |influenced = [[Abu Nu'aym]]<ref name="EI2">{{EI2 | volume=10 | title=al-Ṭabarānī | last=Fierro | first=Maribel |page=10}}</ref> [[Abu Bakr Al-Bazzar]] |works = ''[[Al-Mu'jam al-Kabeer]]'', ''Al-Mu'jam Al-Awsat'', ''Al-Mu'jam As-Saghir'' }}
'''Abu ’l-Qāsim Sulaymān ibn Ayyūb ibn Muṭayyir al-Lakhmī al-Ṭabarānī''' was one of the most important [[hadith]] scholars of his age.<ref name="EI2"/>
==Students== From amongst his students were: Ahmad bin 'Amr bin 'Abdul-Khaliq Al-Basri and Abu Bakr Al-Bazzar.
==Works== He is known primarily for three works on hadith:<ref name="EI2"/> * ''al-Muʿjam al-Kabīr'' – from which he excluded the traditions of Abu Hurayra * ''al-Mu'jam al-Awsat'' – which contains traditions from Abu Hurayra * ''al-Mu'jam as-Saghir'' – which gave a hadith from each of his masters.
==See also== *[[Tabari (name)]] *[[Majma al-Zawa'id]]
