{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}
'''John Beaumont''' (c. 1636{{spaced ndash}}3 July 1701) was an English soldier at the time of the [[Glorious Revolution]] and politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]] between 1685 and 1695.

Beaumont was born at [[Burton, Lincolnshire]], the son of Sapcote Beaumont, 2nd Viscount Beaumont of Swords and his wife Bridget Monson. He was educated at school at [[Market Bosworth]] and was admitted at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]] aged 17 on 3 November 1653.<ref>{{acad|id=BMNT653J|name=Beaumont, John}}</ref> He attended King Charles II in exile and was commissioned a captain in Our Holland Regiment, becoming lieutenant-colonel by 1685.<ref name=Cherry>[https://books.google.com/books?id=U0UkpOJzQmsC&pg=PA17&lpg=PA17&dq=%22Sapcote+Beaumont%22&source=bl&ots=m6-y8LlNNk&sig=UndU3I116H2dJFSADQWeUmILBU0&hl=en&ei=oB_ITMSrGYGUjAeF_NE-&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CCsQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%22Sapcote%20Beaumont%22&f=false George L Cherry ''The Convention Parliament, 1689: a biographical study of its members'']</ref>

In 1685 Beaumont was elected [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Nottingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham]] and held the seat to 1689.<ref>{{Rayment-hc|n|3|date=March 2012}}</ref>

In 1688 Beaumont's regiment, was  marched to Portsmouth under the Duke of Berwick. Beaumont was one of the officers involved in Portsmouth Captains affair when they refused to accept Irish recruits into the regiment against [[James VII and II|King James]] instructions for all regiments to accept a quota of Irish troopers. On 10 September 1688 the officers were brought before a council of war and stripped of their rank.<ref name=Cherry/><ref name=SS>[http://www.spanishsuccession.nl/armies_uk/regiment_f8_webb.html Webb's regiment of foot, later known as 8th Foot]</ref>

Beaumont joined [[William III of England|William of Orange]] at Torbay and on 31 December 1688 and was rewarded with promotion to colonel of the regiment. 
Beaumont was elected MP for [[Hastings (UK Parliament constituency)|Hastings]] in August 1689 and held the seat until 1695.<ref>{{Rayment-hc|h|2|date=March 2012}}</ref>

Beaumont went with his regiment to Ireland, where it landed on 13 August 1689 and took part in the [[Siege of Carrickfergus (1689)|Siege of Carrickfergus]]. It went on to Dundalk and was present at the [[Battle of the Boyne]] in July 1690 . It also took part in the unsuccessful siege of Limerick and was part of the expedition under [[John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough|John Churchill]] that captured Cork and Kinsale. The regiment remained stationed in Ireland in 1691 taking part in the second siege of Limerick and returned to England in February 1692. Beaumont also served in Flanders.<ref name=SS/> He became Governor of [[Dover Castle]]. He left parliament and resigned his commission in 1695.<ref name=Cherry/><ref name=SS/>

In May 1695 after a quarrel in Parliament, Beaumont fought a duel with Sir William Forrester and disarmed him.<ref name=peerage>[http://thepeerage.com/p2809.htm the Peerage.com]</ref>

Beaumont married, firstly, Felicia Mary Fermor, daughter of Sir Hatton Fermor, and secondly  Philippa Carew, daughter of Sir Nicholas Carew. He had no children.<ref name=peerage/>

