{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''The X Factor'' finalists (UK series 8)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Use British English|date=July 2013}} The [[The X Factor (UK series 8)|eighth UK series]] of ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' was broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] from 20 August 2011, with the live shows starting on 8 October 2011. Girl group [[Little Mix]] were the winners, and the runner-up was [[Marcus Collins (singer)|Marcus Collins]]. After ''The X Factor'', several of the contestants went on to release singles, including Little Mix, Collins, [[Amelia Lily]], [[Misha B]], [[Frankie Cocozza]], The Risk and 2 Shoes. On 25 July 2013, three contestants from series 8 - Little Mix, [[Amelia Lily]] and [[Misha B]] - were included in the (three-minute 41-second) X Factor Ultimate Mash-Up, a video trailer for [[The X Factor (UK series 10)|series 10]], a selection of 13 tracks and artists chosen to represent a decade of 'The X Factor' artists impact on the UK national chart.<ref>{{cite web|title = X Factor ultimate mash-up track celebrates the show's tenth birthday|publisher = [[Radio Times]]|url = http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-07-26/x-factor-ultimate-mash-up-track-celebrates-the-shows-tenth-birthday|accessdate = 19 August 2013|deadurl = no|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130822123217/http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-07-26/x-factor-ultimate-mash-up-track-celebrates-the-shows-tenth-birthday|archivedate = 22 August 2013|df = dmy-all}}</ref>
==Boys==
The "Boys" category was mentored by [[Gary Barlow]]. Contestants in this category are males aged 16 to 24. The eight candidates were Frankie Cocozza, Marcus Collins, Craig Colton, Joe Cox, Luke Lucas, James Michael, Max Vickers and John Wilding. Barlow chose:
===Frankie Cocozza=== {{main article|Frankie Cocozza}}
'''Frankie Cocozza''' (born 17 January 1993) is a singer of British and Italian descent, from [[Brighton]]. He auditioned for ''The X Factor'' singing "[[Valerie (The Zutons song)|Valerie]]" and got a yes from each of the four judges and was put through to bootcamp. He then sang "[[Iris (Goo Goo Dolls song)|Iris]]" at bootcamp and was put through to the judges' houses with Gary Barlow as his mentor. At judges' houses he sang "[[What's My Name? (Rihanna song)|What's My Name?]]" and was put through to live shows. For the first live show, he sang "[[The A Team (Ed Sheeran song)|The A Team]]" and was safe. In week two he sang "[[The Scientist (song)|The Scientist]]" but was in the bottom two with Nu Vibe and had to sing again for survival. For his survival song, Cocozza sang "[[Red (Daniel Merriweather song)|Red]]" and was saved by Rowland, Walsh and his mentor who the following week admitted that he should have been sent home. In week three, Cocozza sang "[[Rocks (song)|Rocks]]", and was saved. It was later confirmed that Cocozza had sworn on live TV. In Halloween week, he sang "[[Should I Stay or Should I Go]]" and was safe. In week five, Cocozza sang "[[I Gotta Feeling]]" and was again safe. On 8 November 2011, Cocozza was axed from the show, for breaking the TV show's rules regarding drug use.<ref>{{cite news|title=Frankie Cocozza axed from X Factor over unacceptable behaviour|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8876777/Frankie-Cocozza-axed-from-X-Factor-over-unacceptable-behaviour.html|accessdate=18 September 2012|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=8 November 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312044844/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8876777/Frankie-Cocozza-axed-from-X-Factor-over-unacceptable-behaviour.html|archivedate=12 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
On 5 January 2012, Cocozza entered ''[[Celebrity Big Brother 9]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/05/celebrity-big-brother-2012-lineup|title=Celebrity Big Brother: Frankie Cocozza joins 2012 lineup|first=Press|last=Association|date=5 January 2012|publisher=|via=The Guardian|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927191245/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2012/jan/05/celebrity-big-brother-2012-lineup|archivedate=27 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/x_factor/3984852/X-Factors-Frankie-Cocozza-is-to-join-Celebrity-Big-Brother.html|title=X Factor's Frankie Cocozza is to join Celebrity Big Brother|date=8 December 2011|publisher=|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111217193259/http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/x_factor/3984852/X-Factors-Frankie-Cocozza-is-to-join-Celebrity-Big-Brother.html|archivedate=17 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and came out finishing second to [[Denise Welch]] on 27 January 2012. He also presented MTV's ''[[My Super Sweet 16]]'', which aired on 22 April 2012.{{Citation needed|date=June 2012}} Frankie was also on ''[[The Million Pound Drop Live#Celebrity Games series|The Million Pound Drop: Celebrity Games]]'' alongside his ''Celebrity Big Brother'' housemate [[Natalie Cassidy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facebook.com/notes/the-million-pound-drop/the-million-pound-drop-celebrity-games-summary-friday-20th-july/475969275765173|title=The Million Pound Drop Celebrity Games summary: Friday 20th July|website=www.facebook.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513194729/https://www.facebook.com/notes/the-million-pound-drop/the-million-pound-drop-celebrity-games-summary-friday-20th-july/475969275765173|archivedate=13 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
