===Marcus Collins=== {{Main article|Marcus Collins (singer)}} [[File:Marcus-Collins-X-Factor.jpg|thumb|left|167px|Marcus Collins]] '''Marcus Collins''' (born 15 May 1988) is a hairdresser from [[Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://xfactor.itv.com/2011/finalists/marcus-collins |title=The X Factor – Marcus Collins |publisher=Xfactor.itv.com |accessdate=11 November 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112145959/http://xfactor.itv.com/2011/finalists/marcus-collins |archivedate=12 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Collins was a member of [[Eton Road]], a band that competed during [[The X Factor (UK series 3)|series 3]] of UK ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]''. Following their exit from the show in November 2006 and the departure of lead singer Anthony Hannah, Collins joined Eton Road as a replacement in August 2007. He stayed with the band for about 10&nbsp;months before leaving to pursue a solo career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/875201-marcus-collins-used-to-be-in-x-factor-reject-band-eton-road|title=Marcus Collins used to be in X Factor boy band rejects Eton Road|date=12 September 2011|author=Christopher Hooton|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930122939/http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/875201-marcus-collins-used-to-be-in-x-factor-reject-band-eton-road|archivedate=30 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He is openly [[homosexuality|gay]] and ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper reported that his boyfriend was Eton Road's David Heath.<ref name="sun">{{cite news |last=Connolly |first=Lucy |url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/x_factor/3819485/X-Factors-Marcus-Collins-backed-by-boyfriend-David-Heath.html |title=X Factor's Marcus Collins backed by boyfriend David Heath |work=The Sun |date=17 September 2011 |accessdate=11 November 2011 |location=London |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107180453/http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/x_factor/3819485/X-Factors-Marcus-Collins-backed-by-boyfriend-David-Heath.html |archivedate=7 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 4 December, he was voted through to the live final along with Amelia Lily and Little Mix. He reached the second half of the final on 11 December 2011 with Little Mix and finished second.<ref>{{cite web | title = Marcus Collins keeps smiling through X Factor final defeat to Little Mix - Liverpool Echo | url = http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/marcus-collins-keeps-smiling-through-3357438 | first = Tina | last = Miles | accessdate = 11 October 2013 | deadurl = no | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150111122810/http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/marcus-collins-keeps-smiling-through-3357438 | archivedate = 11 January 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> His self-titled debut album [[Marcus Collins (album)|''Marcus Collins'']] was released on 12 March 2012 with his debut single and the lead single off the album a cover of [[The White Stripes]]' "[[Seven Nation Army#Marcus Collins version|Seven Nation Army]]", which was released on 4 March, the song debuted at No. 9 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web| title = MARCUS COLLINS| url = http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/marcus%20collins/| accessdate = 11 October 2013| deadurl = no| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131014033640/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/marcus%20collins| archivedate = 14 October 2013| df = dmy-all}}</ref>
