==Girls== [[File:Kelly Rowland Walmart Soundcheck cropped.jpg|thumb|180px|The girls were mentored by Kelly Rowland]] The "Girls" category was mentored by [[Kelly Rowland]]. Contestants in this category are females aged 16 to 24. The eight candidates were Misha Bryan, Janet Devlin, Sophie Habibis, Amelia Lily, Melanie McCabe, Holly Repton, Jade Richards and Sarah Watson. Rowland chose:
===Misha B=== {{Main article|Misha B}} [[File:Misha b.jpg|thumb|left|201px|Misha B]] '''Misha Bryan''' (born 10 February 1992), better known as '''Misha B''', is from [[Manchester]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Overwhelming demand to tackle poverty in Manchester|url = http://www.childrenssociety.org.uk/news-views/press-release/overwhelming-demand-tackle-poverty-manchester|accessdate = 19 October 2013|deadurl = no|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131122130837/http://www.childrenssociety.org.uk/news-views/press-release/overwhelming-demand-tackle-poverty-manchester|archivedate = 22 November 2013|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="metro1">{{cite web|last=Elks|first=Sonia|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/877340-the-x-factor-2011-final-16-finalists-revealed-for-live-shows|title=The X Factor 2011 final 16: Finalists revealed as Janet Devlin, Frankie Cocozza, Kitty Brucknell make the cut|work=Metro|accessdate=11 November 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104055315/http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/877340-the-x-factor-2011-final-16-finalists-revealed-for-live-shows|archivedate=4 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Raised from 3-months by her aunt Lily; her father was unknown and mother was unable to carefor her.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sarah Bull|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2030874/X-Factor-2011-Misha-Bryan-labelled-contender-judges-performance-Respect.html|title=The next Aretha Franklin? Teenager Misha Bryan labelled a contender by judges after confident performance of Respect|work=Daily Mail|date=29 August 2011|accessdate=11 November 2011|location=London|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120802052523/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2030874/X-Factor-2011-Misha-Bryan-labelled-contender-judges-performance-Respect.html|archivedate=2 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Misha started singing seriously aged 14, as 'way of understanding myself'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/misha-bryan-biog-pictures-and-videos-274577 Misha Bryan biog, pictures and videos – X Factor finals 2011|title=Misha Bryan biog, pictures and videos|publisher=Mirror Online|accessdate=27 September 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130924065825/http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/misha-bryan-biog-pictures-and-videos-274577|archivedate=24 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010 she started a Vocal Artist course at the Manchester Music Base,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.trafford.ac.uk/|title=Inspiring Minds & Connecting People|work=www3.trafford.ac.uk|accessdate=6 August 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805035902/http://www.trafford.ac.uk/|archivedate=5 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> at [[Trafford College]] and she sang on the open mic circuit and busked in Manchester to tackle her stage fright.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wright|first=Jade |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/in-the-mix/2012/07/06/misha-b-feels-proud-to-play-at-the-anthony-walker-festival-in-liverpool-100252-31334614/|title=Misha B feels proud to play at the Anthony Walker Festival in Liverpool – In The Mix Today – News |publisher=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>
For her audition the 'petite, confident, yet coy, Mancunian' sang "[[Respect (Aretha Franklin song)|Respect]]", 'with the ease and grace of a pro'.<ref name="The Voice Online">The Voice Online: [http://voice-online.co.uk/article/misha-b-hitting-home-run Misha B: Hitting a Home Run|The Voice Online] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725042915/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/misha-b-hitting-home-run |date=25 July 2013 }}</ref> Notably she added one of her own raps to the cover - "how do you make Aretha Franklin's 'Respect' even more sassy? with a rap, of course!"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/08/07/best-x-factor-auditions-cher-lloyd-leona-lewis-james-arthur_n_5657615.html | title=The 20 Best 'X Factor' Auditions Ever: From Cher Lloyd And Leona Lewis To Gamu And James Arthur, Who Wowed Us The Most? | accessdate=7 August 2014 | deadurl=no | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810082936/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/08/07/best-x-factor-auditions-cher-lloyd-leona-lewis-james-arthur_n_5657615.html | archivedate=10 August 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> At bootcamp she sang her version of "[[Survivor (Destiny's Child song)|Survivor]]" and at judges' houses she performed [[Nicki Minaj]] and [[Rihanna]]'s "[[Fly (Nicki Minaj song)|Fly]]". For the first week, Misha sang "[[Rolling in the Deep]]". ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' regarded this performance as a highlight of the series, saying she "oozed star quality from the start... Like a 21st-century [[Grace Jones]] or an urban [[Lady Gaga]], the teenager seemed like a proper pop star already."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8940131/The-top-10-moments-of-X-Factor-2011.html|title=The top 10 moments of X Factor 2011 – Telegraph|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=23 July 2012|location=London|first=Michael|last=Hogan|date=7 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103072015/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8940131/The-top-10-moments-of-X-Factor-2011.html|archivedate=3 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> For the next two weeks Bryan sang "[[Would I Lie to You? (Charles & Eddie song)|Would I Lie to You?]]" and "[[Purple Rain (song)|Purple Rain]]". In week four she sang "[[Tainted Love]]", but was in the bottom two and had to sing for survival in the final showdown against Sophie Habibis. After singing "[[Use Somebody]]" as her survival song, she was unanimously saved by the judges, and Barlow's vote was unnecessary for the result. However it was revealed that Habibis received more votes than Misha B meaning if the result went to deadlock, Habibis would have been saved.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sophie Habibis voted out of 'The X Factor'|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a348281/sophie-habibis-voted-out-of-the-x-factor.html|accessdate=18 May 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120101172734/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a348281/sophie-habibis-voted-out-of-the-x-factor.html|archivedate=1 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> For the fifth week, Misha B sang "[[Proud Mary]]". On week six, Misha sang "[[Born This Way (Lady Gaga song)|Born This Way]]", but again she landed in the final showdown against Brucknell and sang "[[Who You Are (Jessie J song)|Who You Are]]" as her survival song. Walsh (Brucknell's mentor) voted to eliminate her, but Tulisa, Rowland and Barlow voted to save her. However voting statistics revealed that Brucknell received more votes than Misha B meaning if Barlow sent the result went to deadlock, Brucknell would have been saved.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kitty Brucknell leaves 'The X Factor'|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a350662/kitty-brucknell-leaves-the-x-factor.html|accessdate=18 May 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116175115/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a350662/kitty-brucknell-leaves-the-x-factor.html|archivedate=16 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On week seven, Misha sang "[[I Have Nothing]]". Barlow also told Misha B "I want to see the Misha B we saw at the first audition", which led to Misha singing "[[Girls Just Want to Have Fun]]" and "[[Killing Me Softly with His Song]]" on the eighth week. Misha B ended up in the final showdown for the third time in week eight, and sang "Out Here on My Own", with Walsh and Conotstavlos saving her, and Rowland refusing to vote between her and Janet Devlin, meaning Misha B was saved. Barlow also revealed he would have saved her. However it was revealed that Devlin received more votes than Misha B meaning if the result went to deadlock, Devlin would have been sent through to the semi-final and Misha B would have been eliminated.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crying Kelly Rowland refuses to vote so Janet Devlin leaves X Factor|url=http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/gossip/110--pop/crying-kelly-rowland-refuses-to-vote-so-janet-devlin-leaves-x-factor.html|accessdate=18 May 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120102014913/http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/gossip/110--pop/crying-kelly-rowland-refuses-to-vote-so-janet-devlin-leaves-x-factor.html|archivedate=2 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 3rd December, Misha sang "[[Dancing in the Street]]" and "[[Perfect (Pink song)|Perfect]]", but she was voted out of the competition, finishing in 4th place. For her farewell performance "Misha B busted out a short self-penned rap, before segueing into a blinding rendition of Jessie J’s Who You Are."<ref name="telegraph">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8935329/Why-was-Misha-B-knocked-out-of-the-X-Factor.html|title=Why was Misha B knocked out of the X Factor?|accessdate=27 August 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006140603/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8935329/Why-was-Misha-B-knocked-out-of-the-X-Factor.html|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
A variety of sources including ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', [[Digital Spy]] and [[Blues & Soul|bluesandsoul.com]] have considered Misha B as one of the more gifted and exciting acts ever to have come out of a talent competition.<ref name = "telegraph"/><ref>{{cite web|title = Misha B: 'Do You Think of Me' – Single review – Music Singles Review – Digital Spy|url = http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a431604/misha-b-do-you-think-of-me-single-review.html|accessdate = 9 September 2013|deadurl = no|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130911105903/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a431604/misha-b-do-you-think-of-me-single-review.html|archivedate = 11 September 2013|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="Misha B: B">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/806/misha_b_b/|title=Misha B: B+|publisher=bluesandsoul.com|accessdate=27 October 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029053247/http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/806/misha_b_b|archivedate=29 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[BBC 1xtra]] noting her "show-stopping performances", considered her to be one of the most credible artists to emerge from the show and a "break from the traditional X Factor contestant".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/7e1e34c0-6c8f-4699-849b-31cf37935a95#p018dy4q|title=Misha B checks in with CJ Beatz|publisher=BBC Music|accessdate=6 January 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118091754/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/7e1e34c0-6c8f-4699-849b-31cf37935a95#p018dy4q|archivedate=18 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/events/e8vg9r/acts/a8mbj5|title=BBC – 1Xtra Live 2012 – Acts – Misha B|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 December 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214021733/http://www.bbc.co.uk/events/e8vg9r/acts/a8mbj5|archivedate=14 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bryan was involved in a controversy during the third live show when Tulisa Contostavlos accused her of making "mean comments" and Louis Walsh accused her of being a "bully" backstage. No evidence was ever provided to support either allegation and both accusers apologised the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YBfVj5ez20o|title=The X Factor - Misha B|accessdate=7 July 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818121539/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YBfVj5ez20o|archivedate=18 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/sami-brookes-booted-off-x-factor-6360490.html|title=Sami Brookes booted off X Factor - Showbiz - Evening Standard|publisher=Standard.co.uk|accessdate=7 July 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709032728/http://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/sami-brookes-booted-off-x-factor-6360490.html|archivedate=9 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The other two judges and her fellow contestants defended Misha B during and after the show. Judge Gary Barlow later said he believed the wrongful allegations had ended Misha B's chances of winning the competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8935329/Why-was-Misha-B-knocked-out-of-the-X-Factor.html|title=Why was Misha B knocked out of the X Factor? – Telegraph|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|issn=0307-1235|oclc=49632006|accessdate=27 October 2012|first=Michael|last=Hogan|date=5 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091954/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8935329/Why-was-Misha-B-knocked-out-of-the-X-Factor.html|archivedate=5 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8936371/Misha-B-grateful-for-X-Factor-bullying-claims.html|title=Video: Misha B 'grateful' for X Factor bullying claims – Telegraph|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|issn=0307-1235|oclc=49632006|accessdate=27 October 2012|date=5 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103184513/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/x-factor/8936371/Misha-B-grateful-for-X-Factor-bullying-claims.html|archivedate=3 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bryan asked about her experience on X Factor said "I one hundred percent appreciate the platform it gave me...but it's not for the faint-hearted lol. You have to remember that at the end of the day it’s an entertainment show for TV."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.famemagazine.co.uk/2012/07/05/misha-b-interview-life-is-what-you-make-it/#more-60353|title=Misha B Interview: "Life Is What You Make It"|publisher=Famemagazine.co.uk|accessdate=2012-07-07|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120708113443/http://www.famemagazine.co.uk/2012/07/05/misha-b-interview-life-is-what-you-make-it/#more-60353|archivedate=8 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> "Things are said which are out of all of our hands as contestants. I wasn't asked any questions, I was just accused."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/celebrity/celebrity-news/2012/06/28/misha-b-confirms-missy-elliot-collaboration|title=Misha B confirms Missy Elliott collaboration - celebrity news (Glamour.com UK)|work=glamourmagazine.co.uk|year=2012|accessdate=24 July 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727043459/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/celebrity/celebrity-news/2012/06/28/misha-b-confirms-missy-elliot-collaboration|archivedate=27 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Misha B spoke to [[Grammy Awards|grammy.com]] in 2013, "I experienced not only highs but my share of lows on ''The X Factor'', but it has set me up with the thick skin needed for this industry... I will always be grateful for my time on the show. I mean, it got me to where I needed to be."<ref>{{cite web|last=Patterson|first=Joseph|title=Misha B in the UK Spotlight|url=http://www.grammy.com/news/misha-b-in-the-uk-spotlight|publisher=The Recording Academy|accessdate=23 August 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813021414/http://www.grammy.com/news/misha-b-in-the-uk-spotlight|archivedate=13 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Post X Factor Bryan signed to [[Relentless Records]] and released a free fifteen-minute [[mixtape]] entitled ''Why Hello World'' (2012). On 2 May 2012, Misha announced her debut single "[[Home Run (song)|Home Run]]", which was then released in the UK on 15 July.<ref name="officialcharts.com"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Must Listen: Misha B Previews New Single ‘Home Run’ On BBC 1Xtra|url=http://thatgrapejuice.net/2012/05/listen-misha-previews-single-home-run-bbc-1xtra/|accessdate=18 April 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503181712/http://thatgrapejuice.net/2012/05/listen-misha-previews-single-home-run-bbc-1xtra/|archivedate=3 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1050442&c=1|title=Music Week – Music Week – Music business magazine – Midweek Charts: Elton could be heading back to No 1|publisher=musicweek.com|accessdate=18 July 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005093017/http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1050442&c=1|archivedate=5 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the year that followed, Bryan released her second single "[[Do You Think of Me]]" (4 November 2012),<ref name="officialcharts.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/uk-top-40-singles-chart/|title=Official UK Singles Top 40 – 17th November 2012 Official UK Singles Chart Top 40|publisher=officialcharts.com|accessdate=11 November 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204032758/http://www.officialcharts.com/uk-top-40-singles-chart/|archivedate=4 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> her second mix-tape, ''Knock Knock'', (February 2013), and her third single [[Here's to Everything (Ooh La La)]] (29 April 2013). Bryan supported [[Nicki Minaj]] during the United Kingdom leg of her [[Pink Friday: Reloaded Tour]] in October and November 2012. She was nominated in the Best Newcomer category for the [[MOBO Awards]] 2012<ref>{{cite web|title=MOBO Awards 2012 – nominees shortlist revealed|url=http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/mobo-awards-2012-nominees-shortlist-revealed|accessdate=17 September 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806100337/http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/mobo-awards-2012-nominees-shortlist-revealed|archivedate=6 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Misha B is the joint patron of the UK's annual [[The National Diversity Awards|National Diversity Awards]], a celebration of positive diversity role models and community organisations from across the UK,<ref>{{cite web|title = National Diversity Awards land new sponsors|url = http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/national-diversity-awards-land-new-sponsors|accessdate = 20 June 2013|deadurl = no|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130618012516/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/national-diversity-awards-land-new-sponsors|archivedate = 18 June 2013|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Celebrity Patrons – National Diversity Awards|url = http://www.nationaldiversityawards.co.uk/#/celebrity-patrons/4572703201|accessdate = 20 June 2013|deadurl = no|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130706070650/http://www.nationaldiversityawards.co.uk/#/celebrity-patrons/4572703201|archivedate = 6 July 2013|df = dmy-all}}</ref> and an active supporter of [[The Children's Society]] in Manchester <ref>{{cite web|title = 150,000 children living in poverty in Greater Manchester|publisher = Granada - ITV News|url = http://www.itv.com/news/granada/update/2013-11-19/150-000-children-living-in-poverty-in-greater-manchester/|accessdate = 19 November 2013|deadurl = no|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131119212241/http://www.itv.com/news/granada/update/2013-11-19/150-000-children-living-in-poverty-in-greater-manchester/|archivedate = 19 November 2013|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Misha B supporting our work in Greater Manchester|publisher = YouTube|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UVb4FKjGtYw&feature=youtube_gdata|accessdate = 21 November 2013|deadurl = no|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140521230449/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UVb4FKjGtYw&feature=youtube_gdata|archivedate = 21 May 2014|df = dmy-all}}</ref>
