===Amelia Lily=== {{Main article|Amelia Lily}} [[File:Amelia Lily.jpg|thumb|left|159px|Amelia Lily]] '''Amelia Lily''' (born '''Amelia Lily Oliver'''; 16 October 1994)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heatworld.com/Celeb-AZ/Amelia-Lily/ |title=Amelia Lily |publisher=heatworld.com |accessdate=10 December 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126000045/http://www.heatworld.com/Celeb-AZ/Amelia-Lily/ |archivedate=26 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> is from [[Nunthorpe]] in [[Middlesbrough]], where she attended a dance school at the Neptune Centre, [[Berwick Hills]]. She grew up singing in her garden with her friends also taking part in musical theatre.<ref name="metro1"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://xfactor.itv.com/2011/finalists/amelia-lily |title=The X Factor – Amelia Lily |publisher=Xfactor.itv.com |accessdate=11 November 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110122937/http://xfactor.itv.com/2011/finalists/amelia-lily |archivedate=10 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She performed "[[Billie Jean]]" and was the first of the girls' category to be eliminated from the live shows on 9 October by decision of mentor Kelly Rowland, as there was no public vote in the inaugural live show. After Frankie Cocozza was ejected from the show for breaking one of the competition's rules, the public was given a choice to vote, from 10–12 November, for one act which had been eliminated on week 1 to return. Amelia won the vote with over 48% of the vote and replaced Cocozza. She went on to make the final and finished in third place behind Marcus Collins and Little Mix.
Amelia has signed a £500,000 three-album record deal with [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]] subsidiary [[Xenomania]]. Amelia is now coming to the end process of recording her debut album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/s103/the-x-factor/news/a366058/x-factor-amelia-lily-lands-three-album-record-deal.html |title=Amelia Lily lands three album record deal |work=Digital Spy |accessdate=16 February 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217140033/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/s103/the-x-factor/news/a366058/x-factor-amelia-lily-lands-three-album-record-deal.html |archivedate=17 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 29 June 2012, Lily announced her debut album would be released on 29 April 2013,<ref name="albumdetails">{{cite web|title=Amelia Lily confirms debut single 'You Bring Me Joy'|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a390683/amelia-lily-confirms-debut-single-you-bring-me-joy.html|accessdate=29 June 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Fi3jVWCM?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a390683/amelia-lily-confirms-debut-single-you-bring-me-joy.html|archivedate=7 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> though it has since been pushed back to February 2014. The video for "[[You Bring Me Joy (Amelia Lily song)|You Bring Me Joy]]", her debut single, was released in August 2012 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4music.com/the-crush/news/35/Amelia-Lily-You-Bring-Me-Joy|title=Amelia Lily – You Bring Me Joy|publisher=[[4Music]]|accessdate=15 August 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527095801/http://www.4music.com/the-crush/news/35/Amelia-Lily-You-Bring-Me-Joy|archivedate=27 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
