h You (song)|I'm with You]]" - [[Avril Lavigne]] | Song to get you to the final |- style="background:pink;" ! rowspan="2"| Final (Part 1) | "[[Ain't No Other Man]]" - [[Christina Aguilera]] | No theme | rowspan="2"| Eliminated (Third place) |- style="background:pink;" | "[[River Deep – Mountain High]]" - (with [[Kelly Rowland]]) | Mentor duet |}
==Over 25s== [[File:Louis Walsh2009July.jpg|thumb|180px|The over 25s category was mentored by Louis Walsh]] The "Over 25s" category was mentored by [[Louis Walsh]]. Contestants in this category are of either gender, aged 25 or over. There is no upper age limit. The eight candidates were Sami Brookes, Kitty Brucknell, Goldie Cheung, Joseph Gilligan, Jonjo Kerr, [[Carolynne Poole]], Johnny Robinson and Terry Winstanley. Walsh chose:
===Sami Brookes=== {{redirect|Samantha Brookes|the pageant model|Samantha Brooks}} '''Samantha "Sami" Brookes''' is from [[Rhyl]], [[Denbighshire]]. She replaced contestant Goldie Cheung, who left at the end of judges' houses. For the first live show, she sang [[Free (Ultra Naté song)|Free]], and was kept in the competition. The following weeks she sang "[[I Will Always Love You (Whitney Houston version)|I Will Always Love You]]" and "[[If I Could Turn Back Time]]". She was placed in the bottom two in the third week, along with fellow Over 25er Kitty Brucknell. She performed "[[(You Make Me Feel Like) A Natural Woman]]" in the final showdown. The vote allowed Walsh to send the vote to deadlock, as although Rowland and Barlow sent Brookes home, Contostavlos opted against Brucknell. However, Walsh sent Brookes home, thus eliminating her from the competition. Voting statistics later revealed that Brookes had received more votes from the public than Brucknell meaning if Walsh sent the result to deadlock, Brookes would have been saved.<ref>{{cite web|title=X Factor 2011 voting figures revealed: Girl acts won every single week|url=http://metro.co.uk/2011/12/12/x-factor-2011-voting-figures-revealed-girl-acts-won-every-single-week-252825/|work=Metro|accessdate=22 August 2013|author=Christopher Hooton|date=12 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517181341/http://metro.co.uk/2011/12/12/x-factor-2011-voting-figures-revealed-girl-acts-won-every-single-week-252825/|archivedate=17 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Janet Devlin won The X Factor vote for the first four weeks, with Little Mix failing to win until week seven - see full voting results since week one|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/janet-devlin-won-the-x-factor-281230|accessdate=22 August 2013|newspaper=Daily Mirror|date=11 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140115011148/http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/janet-devlin-won-the-x-factor-281230|archivedate=15 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
After her elimination, Brookes gave interviews accusing Walsh of playing favorites with Brucknell while ignoring her ideas and song lists, and forcing her to perform a Cher song in week 3 instead of a rock number.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sami Brookes blames Louis Walsh for X Factor exit and denies Misha B bully claims|url=http://metro.co.uk/2011/10/24/sami-brookes-blames-louis-walsh-for-x-factor-exit-and-denies-misha-b-bully-claims-193135/|work=Metro|publisher=Metro.co|accessdate=22 August 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513134440/http://metro.co.uk/2011/10/24/sami-brookes-blames-louis-walsh-for-x-factor-exit-and-denies-misha-b-bully-claims-193135/|archivedate=13 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She, however, later stated that she only appeared on the show to boost her profile for a musical theatre career instead of a pop career and a recording contract.
