===Little Mix=== {{Main article|Little Mix}} [[File:Little mixx.jpg|thumb|left|Leigh-Anne, Perrie, Jade and Jesy]] '''Little Mix''' (formerly known as '''Rhythmix''') are a four-piece girl group made up of former barmaid Jesy Nelson from Essex,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2059019/Little-Mixs-Jesy-Nelson-plans-rise-haters-upsetting-fat-jibes.html|title=Little Mix's Jesy Nelson plans to rise above her haters after upsetting 'fat' jibes|work=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=8 November 2011|location=London|first=Georgina|last=Littlejohn|date=9 November 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120801090948/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2059019/Little-Mixs-Jesy-Nelson-plans-rise-haters-upsetting-fat-jibes.html|archivedate=1 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> former Pizza Hut waitress Leigh-Anne Pinnock from [[High Wycombe]], and [[South Shields]] students Perrie Edwards and Jade Thirlwall.<ref name="metro1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://xfactor.itv.com/2011/finalists/rhythmix|title=The X Factor – Little Mix|publisher=[[itv.com]]|accessdate=11 November 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027024554/http://xfactor.itv.com/2011/finalists/rhythmix|archivedate=27 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Originally known as Rhythmix, the band was formed by the judges at bootcamp, during which they were auditioning as soloists, but failed to advance for the Girls category for Judges' Houses. On 26 October 2011, Rhythmix announced that they would change their name following a dispute with [[Rhythmix|a children's music charity of the same name]], after the programme tried to trademark "Rhythmix" in Europe. After some disagreement between [[Syco]] and the charity,<ref name=guardian-dec2011>{{cite news|last=Michaels|first=Sean|title=Nirvana's Smells Like Teen Spirit to be re-released for Christmas|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/dec/07/nirvana-smells-like-teen-spirit-christmas?newsfeed=true|accessdate=8 December 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|date=7 December 2011|location=London|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005134742/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/dec/07/nirvana-smells-like-teen-spirit-christmas?newsfeed=true|archivedate=5 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> a resolution was reached and Cowell donated an undisclosed sum to the charity.<ref name=glamour-dec-11>{{cite web|title=Simon Cowell donates money to Rhythmix charity|url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/celebrity/celebrity-news/2011/10/26/rhythmix-charity-open-letter-simon-cowell|work=Glamour|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6GGJgv053?url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/celebrity/celebrity-news/2011/10/26/rhythmix-charity-open-letter-simon-cowell|archivedate=30 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A spokesperson for ''The X Factor'' said, "At the request of the charity Rhythmix, the members of the girl group Rhythmix have decided to change their name, a decision which has the support of Syco and TalkbackTHAMES. The group's new name will be announced in due course". It was reported that the band decided to make the change, despite no legal reason to do so, to avoid any difficulties for the charity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a347661/x-factor-rhythmix-to-change-name-following-charity-pressure.html |title='X Factor' Rhythmix to change name following charity pressure – X Factor News – TV |work=Digital Spy |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=11 November 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028141016/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s103/the-x-factor/news/a347661/x-factor-rhythmix-to-change-name-following-charity-pressure.html |archivedate=28 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> They announced that they would now be known as Little Mix on 28 October 2011 following on from this, the band said: "We all agreed on it, including Tulisa, because it just felt right". Little Mix became the first girl band in the history of ''The X Factor'' to make it to the final live show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/tv/x-factor/2011/12/04/misha-b-kicked-off-x-factor-as-little-mix-make-history-115875-23610576/|title=Misha B kicked off X Factor as Little Mix make history|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=4 December 2011|accessdate=11 December 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111208015821/http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/tv/x-factor/2011/12/04/misha-b-kicked-off-x-factor-as-little-mix-make-history-115875-23610576/|archivedate=8 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They reached the final two on 10 December 2011, and won the show on 11 December 2011, making them the first group to win ''The X Factor''. The prize was a £1 million recording contract with [[Syco]], in association with [[Sony Music]], although the majority of it goes towards recording and marketing costs. It also includes a stated cash advance of £150,000.
Little Mix have since released twelve singles as of September 2016, all of which have charted in the top 20, and 3 number one singles; "[[Cannonball (Damien Rice song)|Cannonball]]", "[[Wings (Little Mix song)|Wings]]", and [[Black Magic (Little Mix song)|Black Magic]]. Their debut album ''[[DNA (Little Mix album)|DNA]]'' charted at number three on the [[UK Albums Chart]], and also in the top 5 in the USA. On 23 September 2013, they debuted "[[Move (Little Mix song)|Move]]" (the first single from their second album ''[[Salute (Little Mix album)|Salute]]''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/09/23/little-mix-debut-new-single-move-on-radio-1-4089834/|title=Little Mix debut new single Move on Nick Grimshaw's Radio 1 Breakfast Show|date=23 September 2013|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|accessdate=27 September 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926052013/http://metro.co.uk/2013/09/23/little-mix-debut-new-single-move-on-radio-1-4089834/|archivedate=26 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and on 21 May 2015, debuted Black Magic, the first song from their third album [[Get Weird]], which sold double platinum in the UK, and earned strong chart placings worldwide. On November 18 2016 their 4th album Glory Days was released reaching no. one in the uk official charts
